
Option 1 â€”Run Prometheus with a simple Docker command
------------------------------------------------------
1. Create a Prometheus configuration file
   Make a file called prometheus.yml in your current directory:
global:
  scrape_interval: 15s

scrape_configs:
  - job_name: "prometheus"
    static_configs:
      - targets: ["localhost:9090"]
 #This tells Prometheus to scrape itself every 15 seconds.

2. Run Prometheus in Docker
docker run -d \
  --name=prometheus \
  -p 9090:9090 \
  -v $(pwd)/prometheus.yml:/etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml \
  prom/prometheus
Explanation:
-d â†’ run in detached mode
--name â†’ container name
-p 9090:9090 â†’ expose Prometheus web UI on port 9090
-v â†’ mount local config into the container

3. Open Prometheus UI
   Visit: ðŸ‘‰ http://localhost:9090

Option 2 â€” Use Docker Compose (recommended for larger setups)
-------------------------------------------------------------
Create a file named docker-compose.yml:
version: "3"
services:
  prometheus:
    image: prom/prometheus
    container_name: prometheus
    volumes:
      - ./prometheus.yml:/etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml
    ports:
      - "9090:9090"
    restart: unless-stopped

Then start it with: docker compose up -d
Verify Prometheus is running
Check container logs: docker logs prometheus
You should see something like:  level=info msg="Server is ready to receive web requests."





   
